03/10/2003
BELGRADE, Serbia-Montenegro -- The Serbian government faces a no-confidence vote in parliament on 14 October at the request of the opposition Democratic Party of Serbia, led by former Yugoslav President Vojislav Kostunica. The Serbian Radical Party, led by Vojislav Seselj, also pushed for the vote.
In other news, the Serbia-Montenegro Supreme Defence Council recommended on Thursday (2 October) that the defence ministry begin providing access to military documents. Prosecutors with the UN war crimes tribunal have sought access to the documents for use as evidence. (B92, Tanjug, FoNet, BBC - 02/10/03)
